name: De Bazel
tags: Building Uses - office - monument - warehouse; Structural Types - highrise; Architectural Style - art deco; Materials - glass - granite - brick - concrete
description:
Description
• Architect: Karel de Bazel.

___________________________________________________________



• The architect died in 1923, three years before the building would be completed. The construction was continued and completed by his chef de bureau C. van de Linde, along with designer Adolf Leonard Gendt. The sculptures are the work of Joseph Mendes da Costa, Lambertus Zijl and Hendrik A. van den Eijnde. The stained glass windows are the design of Anthony Derk Inderen and  Joep Nicolas.



• After serving many years as an office for the 'Nederlandse Handelsmaatschappij' (NHM) and ABN/AMRO Bank this monumental building was renovated by Claus & Kaan after which it became the city archive of Amsterdam.



• The concrete skeleton of the building - designed by ADN of Gendt - is filled with vowels, alternated with strips of granite. The massiveness of the building is tempered by a number of vertical jump back in the facade. 



• The building is two light courts. These were originally only interrupted by a glass floor on the third floor. In the open light construction and the detailing of the exterior is the work of kinship with the American architect Frank Lloyd Wright and Louis Sullivan felt. The renovation was in 2006 the light courts again restored to its former state. Almost all the interior parts of the building, such as floor mosaics, air frames, telephone booths and the establishment of the offices, including furniture, were also designed by the Basel. Although many in the interior has been postponed, including the large conference room on the third floor has been preserved in their original state. 



• The building was declared a monument in 1991.

description:

• Architect: Hendrick de Keyser.

name: Montelbaanstoren
tags: Building Uses - unused - observation; Structural Types - tower - other; Materials - glass - limestone - brick
description:
Description
• Architect: Hendrick de Keyser.

___________________________________________________________



• This tower was built in 1516 to the Old Schans for defense purposes. 



• The origin of the name is unknown. The tower is nicknamed Malle Jaap, as the bells of the tower spontaneously began to play ever irregular times. 



• The Montelbaanstoren was built when the medieval Amsterdam was extended by the industrial Lastage to the city to withdraw. This was on the east side dug, a new canal, the Oude Schans. Where it IJ approached was a defense tower put down.



• In 1606 the tower lost its defensive function. In same year, the tower-peak, a decorative crown in Renaissance style, was added after a design by architect Hendrick de Keyser. In de toren kwam een uurwerk, en enkele luidklokken. In 1610 the tower collapsed, which is based on sod (called skins), skewed. It had to be then rectified. 



• Rembrandt, who lived in the area, drew the tower in 1644, but without the construction of De Keyser. 



• In 1852 the tower threatened to be demolished, but since 1878, the City Water Office is located in the tower. Until 2006 was housed the Department of Execution of the service sector Water Sewerage and Water. In 2006 the City Water Office left to a new location and the tower was thoroughly restored. The destination of the tower is uncertain.

description:
Description
- Architect: 24H>Architecture

http://www.24h.eu/



- In the area Hatert, at the edge of the city of Nijmegen, the housing corporations Portaal and Talis organize a great renewal operation. Most of the housing at present does not comply with contemporary standards or needs a substantial make over.



- For this operation the city of Nijmegen worked in cooperation with the office of Khandekar towards a master plan in which most of the present houses are renovated or renewed. Besides that in the open areas of the neighborhood various new housing projects will be realized.



- A twelve storey apartment tower is planned in the very centre of Hatert, which is presently empty. The building is meant to form the new ‘crown’ of Hatert.



- 24H>architecture designed a sturdy tower with free formed balconies around, which make a recognizable sculpture from all around. The parking for the apartment is organized underneath a raised deck that will function as a new public space for citizens of Hatert. Underneath the housing program the ground floor will be used as a community health centre. 



Rendering Video: http://demo.drupsteen.com/hatert/content/javaversie.html

description:
Description
• The elevations of white travertine cladding and tinted glass in bronze-coloured frames look rational and abstract yet have been given every aesthetic consideration. Each successive storey widens by just a few centimeters as a perspective-correcting device.



• After an interior reconstruction in 2012, the fourth tower of the Europoint complex was baptized 'Rotterdam Science Tower'. In cooperation with the Erasmus University Medical Center, several floors were changed into laboratories. The office space is merely intended for commercial partners which have strong affinity with medical sciences.

--------------------------------------------------------------------

description:
Description

___________________________________________________________



• Officialy opened on october 12, 2007.



• The building won the annual Emporis Skyscraper Award in 2007. "The building was chosen by our jury for its elegant reinterpretation of classic high-rise architecture, its contextual approach to a limited site, and its efficient program for accommodating new entrants to the housing market."



• Hague's tallest all-residential tower.



• Occupies a site measuring just 30 x 35 metres.



• The design was inspired by the Flatiron Building in New York City.



• The terrace on the 41st floor is accessed via a dedicated panoramic glass lift.



• 300 studios for young people and 51 luxury rental apartments.

description:
Description
• On August 1 1674 the center part of the church was destroyed by a hurricane, seperating the tower with the rest of the church, so since then tower became world's tallest free-standing one (till 1884). To celebrate the 750 anniversary of the church in 2004 the old center part of the church was reconstructed with a 42 meter tall steel frame, filling the gap between tower and church.

• A 105 meter tall replica was built in Nagasaki.

name: The Harbour City
tags: Building Uses - residential - garden - parking garage - restaurant - retail - fitness center; Structural Types - highrise; Architectural Style - brutalist - modern; Materials - glass - concrete
description:
Description
The Harbour City is a 37 floor tower that will bring new life to Fort Street. For years Fort Street was a rundown area filled with Strip Clubs and Brothels. These however, are slowly relocating as new developents force them out. Another notable developemnt in the fort street area is the 29 floor Simpson Grierson Tower presently under construction furthur down Fort Street.





The building is to have a curved cylindrical corner that wraps around Gore and Fort streets providing an interesting feature to the streetscape. It will include shops and cafes, and will attract large amounts of pedestrains to Fort Street.



News:

10 Jun 04

RESIDENCES @ HARBOURCITY GETS GREEN LIGHT

The Auckland City Council has approved contrustion, which will start in a month, and take around 22 months to complete.

name: Ryugyong Hotel
tags: Building Uses - mixed use - hotel - office - residential - restaurant; Structural Types - highrise - revolving floor; Architectural Style - modern; Materials - concrete, reinforced
description:
Description
Architect: Baikdoosan Architects



This project was built in anticipation of a joint Olympic Games between North and South Korea.  when the plans for that never materialized, this project became abandoned.  Despite its towering presence over Pyongyang, official maps do not show its location.  



When topped-out, the Ryugyong Hotel was the ninth tallest highrise building in the world by roof height.



Prior to the construction of Taipei 101, this was the only structure in the world outside of the United States with over 100 floors.



The project was on hold for 16 years (1992-2008) before it finally resumed construction.



The planned opening date for the hotel is April 15th 2012; the 100th anniversary of the birth of President Kim Il Sung.
